The paper deals with a random linear system with input distributions, which is a typical problem in information theory and communication systems. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.COMM (Communications and Networking) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes, which are commonly used in communication systems, further supporting the likelihood of cs.COMM. The paper also mentions the use of the approximate message passing (AMP) algorithm, which is a popular algorithm in signal processing and machine learning, making cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper discusses the achievable rate of the AMP algorithm, which is a performance metric commonly used in information theory and communication systems, further supporting the likelihood of cs.IT and cs.COMM.
